sers & Lyricists Awards |date=December 2, 2019 |accessdate=December 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"4\"| [[18th Visual Effects Society Awards|Visual Effects Society Awards]]\n|scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"4\"|January 29, 2020\n|Outstanding Visual Effects in an Animated Feature\n|Steve Goldberg, Peter Del Vecho, Mark Hammel and Michael Giaimo\n|{{nom}}\n|scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://visualeffectssociety.com/press-releases/visual-effects-society-announces-winners-of-the-18th-annual-ves-awards/|title=Visual Effects Society Announces Winners of the 18th Annual VES Awards|last=|first=|date=January 30, 2020|website=Visual Effects Society|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n|Outstanding Animated Character in an Animated Feature\n|Svetla Radivoeva, Marc Bryant, Richard E. Lehmann and Cameron Black {{Small|(for \"The Water N\u00f8kk)}}\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Outstanding Created Environment in an Animated Feature\n|Samy Segura, Jay V. Jackson, Justin Cram and Scott Townsend {{Small|(for \"Giants' Gorge\")}}\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Outstanding Effects Simulations in an Animated Feature\n|Erin V. Ramos, Scott Townsend, Thomas Wickes and Rattanin Sirinaruemarn \n|{{Won}}\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q24733929|q=no|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|s=no|wikt=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|c=Category:Frozen 2|display=''Frozen II''}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|title=Frozen II}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|title=Frozen II}}\n* {{Metacritic film|title=Frozen II}}\n* {{AllMovie title|title=Frozen II}}\n* {{bcdb title|title=Frozen II}}\n* {{mojo title|title=Frozen II}}\n* [http://www.disneyanimation.com/projects/frozen2 ''Frozen II''] at [[Walt Disney Animation Studios]]\n\n{{Frozen}}\n{{Disney theatrical animated features}}\n{{Walt Disney Animation Studios}}\n{{The Snow Queen}}\n{{Chris Buck}}\n{{Jennifer Lee (filmmaker)}}\n{{Portal bar|Disney|Animation|Cartoon|Film}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2019 3D films]]\n[[Category:2019 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2010s musical drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s sequel films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:Animated musical films]]\n[[Category:Frozen (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Chris Buck]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jennifer Lee (filmmaker)]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Peter Del Vecho]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Christophe Beck]]\n[[Category:Films set in Scandinavia]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jennifer Lee (filmmaker)]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Animation Studios films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:American musical drama films]]\n", "name_user": "Wallyfromdilbert", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(remove details from lead not supported by main body + remove Daily Mail cite)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frozen_II"}
{"title_page": "George D. Lundberg", "text_new": "{{short description|American pathologist and writer (born 1933)}}\n'''George David Theodore Lundberg''' (born March 21, 1933) is an American [[board certified|board-certified]] [[pathologist]] and writer.<ref>[http://sites.rootsweb.com/~alcsilve/lundbergg.html \"George David Lundberg, M.D.\"]. Retrieved December 08, 2018.</ref> \n\nFor seventeen years, from 1982 to 1999, Lundberg served as editor-in-chief of the ''[[JAMA (journal)|Journal of the American Medical Association]]'' (''JAMA''), followed by a decade (February 1999 to January 2009) as the editor-in-chief of [[Medscape]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Romaine|first=M|last2=Zatz|first2=S|last3=Brown|first3=K|last4=Lundberg|first4=GD|year=2009|title=So long but not farewell: ''The Medscape Journal of Medicine'' (1999-2009)|url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/587141|journal=Medscape Journal of Medicine|volume=11|issue=1|page=33|pmid=19295954|url-access=registration|accessdate=21 February 2009}}</ref> where he has served as [[editor-at-large]] for the site since 2013.<ref>[https://www.medscape.com/author/george-lundberg \"George D. Lundberg, MD\"]. [[Medscape]]. Retrieved December 08, 2018.</ref> Lundberg is president and chair of the [http://www.lundberginstitute.org/ Lundberg Institute], which presents annual lectures in collaboration with the [https://www.commonwealthclub.org/ Commonwealth Club of California] in San Francisco. Lundberg has been elected to the [[National Academy of Medicine]].<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref>\n\nLundberg\u2019s varied career has comprised four phases of roughly equal duration:\n\n(1) Government service (US Army, LTC, [[Vietnam Era]], in Los Angeles),\n\n(2) Full-time academia ([[University of Southern California]] and [[University of California, Davis]]),\n\n(3) Not-for-profit publishing ([[American Medical Association]]), and\n\n(4) For-profit and not-for-profit entrepreneurship: [[Medscape]] from [[WebMD]]; [https://www.medpagetoday.com/ MedPage Today] from [[Everyday Health]]; [https://www.rennovahealth.com/brands/collabrx CollabRx] (chief medical officer and editor-in-chief); [https://www.selfcarecatalysts.com/ Self-Care Catalysts]; [https://www.cancercommons.org/ Cancer Commons] (editor-in-chief); [[Cureus]] (executive advisor); the [http://www.lundberginstitute.org/ Lundberg Institute] (president and board chair); the Curious Dr. George Blog (through the [http://www.lundberginstitute.org/ Lundberg Institute], editor-in-chief); and [https://www.potentiametrics.com/ PotentiaMetrics].\n\nAs of 2020, Lundberg continues his valuable work through several of these same ventures and venues. He has recently acted as consulting professor of pathology and health research and policy at [[Stanford University]], sits on the medical advisory board of Cancer Commons and on the board of visitors at the [[University of Alabama at Birmingham]], and is Clinical Professor of Pathology at [https://www.feinberg.northwestern.edu/ Northwestern University\u2019s Feinberg School of Medicine]. \n\n== Education ==\nLundberg possesses degrees from eight different colleges and universities. First attending college at the age of 15, he received his AA degree in pre-med from [[North Park Junior College]] in Chicago in 1950 and a BS in chemistry from the [[University of Alabama]] in 1952. Beginning his medical work as an operating room janitor and promoted to ward orderly during pre-med, Lundberg obtained his MD from the [[Medical College of Alabama]] in 1957 and performed a rotating clinical internship in Honolulu as part of an 11-year stint in the Regular US Army Medical Corps ([[Vietnam Era]]). His residency, from 1958 to 1962, was in anatomic and clinical pathology at [[Brooke General Hospital]], Fort Sam Houston, Texas; Lundberg\u2019s degrees also include an MS in pathology from [[Baylor University]]. He has held academic professorial appointments from six universities, including [[Harvard University|Harvard]] and [[Stanford University|Stanford]] universities.<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref>\n\n== Career, Professional Life, and Research ==\nDuring his fourth year of medical school, Lundberg voluntarily enlisted in the Army and spent the next 11 years training in and then practicing pathology as a second lieutenant and then lieutenant colonel.<ref>\u201cThe Online Medicine Man\u201d. ''College News'', University of Alabama College of Arts and Sciences. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref> He was on military staff duty at [https://www.nps.gov/prsf/learn/historyculture/letterman-complex.htm Letterman General Hospita]l on the [https://www.presidio.gov/ Presidio of San Francisco] when he first encountered computers in 1963, automating the [http://www.cttr.org/ California Tumor Tissue Registry]. Although never a self-proclaimed \u201ctechie,\u201d he has utilized computers in the practice of medicine from 1963 until today.<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref>\n\nLundberg was chief pathologist as an Lieutenant Colonel at [[William Beaumont General Hospital]] in El Paso from 1964 to 1967, placing computers into the clinical laboratory as a pioneer early adopter in 1966. Although Lundberg stated that \u201cthe Army treated me very well,\u201d he and his wife had three young children and \u201cthey kept making me move around,\u201d so he chose to leave the Army, becoming Associate Professor of Pathology at the [[University of Southern California]] in Los Angeles in 1967.<ref>\u201cThe Online Medicine Man\u201d. ''College News'', University of Alabama College of Arts and Sciences. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref> There, Lundberg focused on research and teaching on drug-induced diseases. Promoted to Assistant Director of Laboratories and Pathology at the [[Los Angeles County \u2013 USC Medical Center|Los Angeles County\u2013USC Medical Center]] in 1968 (and later becoming Associate Director in 1972), he led the growth of this department to become the world\u2019s largest and most productive hospital laboratory between 1968 and 1977. In 1969, Lundberg placed computers into the clinical laboratory while concurrently abolishing the \u201cration stamp\u201d approach to controlling excess lab test use.<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref><ref>\u201cThe Online Medicine Man\u201d. ''College News'', University of Alabama College of Arts and Sciences. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref>\n\nLeveraging the tragic 1969 death of American media personality [[Diane Linkletter|Art Linkletter\u2019s daughter Diane]], Lundberg obtained Los Angeles County funding to build and maintain a 24/7 hospital clinical toxicology lab that became a model for the field. As part of this process, Lundberg's group invented (and was credited with) and implemented the [https://www.legacyhealth.org/for-health-professionals/refer-a-patient/laboratory-services/critical-values-and-reference-ranges.aspx critical laboratory value] system, a system that quickly became (and remains) the standard of hospital laboratory practice all over the world.<ref>Lippi, G; Mattiuzi, C (2016, October). \u201cCritical laboratory values communications: summary recommendations from available guidelines\u201d. ''Annals of Translational Medicine.'' '''4''' (20): 400. doi:10.21037/atm.2016.09.36. Retrieved March 29, 2020.</ref><ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref> The term \u201ccritical laboratory value,\u201d also known as critical result, panic value, or alert value, was defined by Lundberg himself in 1972 as a result that represents a pathophysiological state different from normal, one that poses risk to a patient's life unless an immediate action is taken.<ref>Rocha, BCB; Alves, JAR; Pinto, FPD; Mendes, ME; Sumita, NM (2016). \u201cThe critical value concept in clinical laboratory\u201d. ''Brazilian Journal of Pathology and Laboratory Medicine.'' '''52''' (1). Retrieved March 28, 2020.</ref><ref>Lundberg G (1972). \u201cWhen to panic over an abnormal value\u201d. ''Medical Laboratory Observer.'' '''4''': 47\u201354.</ref>\n\nBy the early 1970s, the Los Angeles County emergency room was seeing 50 to 70 patients a day with illnesses suspected to be drug related.<ref>Lundberg, GD; Wahlberg, CB; Pantlik, VA (1974). \u201cFrequency of clinical toxicology test-ordering (primarily overdose cases) and results in a large urban general hospital\u201d. ''Clinical Chemistry''. '''20''' (2): 121\u20135. Retrieved March 27, 2020.</ref> Lundberg responded to the street drug epidemic by establishing a \u201cStreet Drug Identification Program\u201d so that users could learn the real identity of the substances they were buying; he publicized this information through a weekly Dope Scoreboard in the Los Angeles Free Press.<ref>Lundberg, GD; Gupta, RC; Montgomery, S (1974, April 1). \u201cA Street Drug Identification Program\u201d. ''Laboratory Medicine.'' '''5''' (4): 8\u201310. doi.org/10.1093/labmed/5.4.8. Retrieved March 27, 2020.</ref> In the mid-1970s, Lundberg invented the patient-focused (now termed \u201cpatient-centered\u201d) approach to laboratory medicine, organizing the laboratory around turnaround times for analytical test performance needed to make appropriate and timely clinical decisions.<ref>Benson, ES (1977, January 3). \u201cManaging the Patient-Focused Laboratory\u201d. ''JAMA.'' '''237''' (1): 69. doi:10.1001/jama.1977.03270280071032. Retrieved March 27, 2020.</ref><ref>Lundberg, GD (1975). ''Managing the Patient-Focused Laboratory''. Oradell, NJ: Medical Economics Publishing Company. 379 pp.</ref>\n\nIn 1977 Lundberg became Professor and Chair of Pathology at [[UC Davis School of Medicine]]. Here, with others, in 1980 he revised an entire 4-year medical school curriculum using a modified Delphi approach, implementing it in less than one year, with student achievement outcome measures set and accomplished.<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref>\n\n===''JAMA''===\nFor 20 years, Lundberg had practiced pathology in hospitals, in academia, and in the military, but in 1982, he received an offer that propelled him in a new direction, one that led him to a new kind of medical pioneering. Lundberg had been sitting on the ''[[JAMA (journal)|Journal of the American Medical Association]]''\u2019s (''JAMA'') editorial board since 1974 and even started his own column for the journal. By 1981, however, the [[American Medical Association]] wanted a new editor-in-chief, and Lundberg was their first choice.<ref>\u201cThe Online Medicine Man\u201d. ''College News'', University of Alabama College of Arts and Sciences. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref>\n\nAs editor-in-chief, Lundberg had editorial responsibility for all 10 [[American Medical Association|AMA]] specialty journals. He also created the concept of \u201ctheme issues\u201d for the journal to achieve a host of editorial and public health/policy objectives, in which the editorial team selected relevant papers based on topics that were of particular interest to readers. Such issues covered topics like prevention of nuclear war, alternative medicine, Hispanic and African American health, boxing, guns and violence, women\u2019s health, caring for the uninsured, alcohol, and tobacco.<ref>Lundberg, GD (2019, May 15). \u201cThe Art and Science of JAMA, Then and Now\u201d. ''Medscape.'' Retrieved March 28, 2020.</ref> \u201cI think we published eight or nine tobacco-themed issues over the years, and those publications are credited with being central to the movement of stopping tobacco smoking for most of America,\u201d Lundberg said. \u201cThat was hugely important.\u201d<ref>\u201cThe Online Medicine Man\u201d. ''College News'', University of Alabama College of Arts and Sciences. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref><ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref> Lundberg also began a series in ''JAMA'', \u201cToward Optimal Laboratory Use,\u201d that introduced the physicians of the world to algorithms (this series ran for 30 years) and also resulted in the book ''Using the Clinical Laboratory in Medical Decision Making''.<ref>Lundberg, GD (1983). ''Using the Clinical Laboratory in Medical Decision Making.'' Chicago: ASCP Press. 327 pp.</ref>\n\nIn 1987 Lundberg established peer review as a \u201cscience\u201d though the quadrennial International Congress on Peer Review in Biomedical Publication. Lundberg hosted medical television education programs on cable television; he achieved high visibility in the public media through his consideration of public journalists as colleagues who could help to educate the public about important advances in medical and health knowledge. And he involved promising medical students in becoming medical editors, with prominent alumni of this program including Drs [[Erica Frank]], [[Scott Gottlieb]], and [https://retractionwatch.com/meet-the-retraction-watch-staff/about/ Ivan Oransky]. With others at [https://wame.org/report-of-the-bellagio-conference Bellagio in 1995], Lundberg created the [[World Association of Medical Editors]] (WAME).<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref>\n\nIn 1999 Lundberg was fired from his position at ''JAMA'' after the publishing of a controversial article on how college students define [[oral sex]]<ref>Sanders, SA; Reinisch, JM (1999, January 20). \u201cWould You Say You \u2018Had Sex\u2019 If \u2026 ?\u201d ''JAMA.'' '''281''' (3): 275\u20137. doi:10.1001/jama.281.3.275. Retrieved March 27, 2020.</ref>; the article coincided with related issues in U.S. [[Impeachment of Bill Clinton|President Clinton's impeachment trial]].<ref>\"Editor Fired Over Sex Article\". [[CBS News]]. Retrieved December 08, 2018.</ref> Executives from the [[American Medical Association]], stating that the article had nothing to do with medicine and that it jeopardized the high standard of the journal, attempted to prevent publication, but failed.<ref>\"Health Editor fired over oral sex story\". [[BBC News]]. Retrieved December 08, 2018.</ref><ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref> Longtime observers of medicine criticized the firing, saying good journals often speed publication of articles relevant to public health or public debate: \u201cI think this is a tragedy, since George Lundberg is a giant in the field of American medical publishing, and under his leadership, the journal flourished,\u201d said [[Arthur Caplan]], director of bioethics at the [[University of Pennsylvania]]; [[June Reinisch|June M. Reinisch]], co-author of the article in the January 20 issue of ''JAMA'', said she was \u201cabsolutely shocked\u201d by the firing and that there had been nothing unusual about ''JAMA''\u2019s handling of the article.<ref>Coleman, BC (1999, January 15). \u201c''JAMA'' Editor Fired Over Sex Article\u201d. ''AP News.'' Retrieved November 21, 2019.</ref>\n\nBy the time Lundberg left ''JAMA'' in 1999, he\u2019d helped to run and create 21 international editions in 13 languages\u2014covering everywhere from Moscow to Buenos Aires. He had doubled the worldwide circulation of the print ''JAMA'' to the world\u2019s largest print circulation of any general medical journal and increased the JAMA SCI Impact factor from about 4 to nearly 20.<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref><ref>\u201cThe Online Medicine Man\u201d. ''College News'', University of Alabama College of Arts and Sciences. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref>\n\n=== The Online Medicine Man <ref>The title of this section reflects the title of the following article: \u201cThe Online Medicine Man\u201d. ''College News'', University of Alabama College of Arts and Sciences. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref>===\nLundberg, along with a few other pioneers, invented \u201cInternet Medicine\u201d in the late 1990s. From 1999 to 2009 and again in 2013\u20132019, Lundberg was the editor of ''[[Medscape]]'' (from [[WebMD]]), where he currently serves as editor-at-large for the site. During a 2001\u20132002 timeframe, Lundberg invented the concurrent triple medium (\u201cread, listen, watch, all on the same page\u201d) video editorial, and continues to publish such regularly.<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref>\n\nLundberg\u2019s additional and notable online medical presence includes [[CollabRx]] (chief medical officer and editor-in-chief, 2010\u20132018); the precision oncology of [https://www.cancercommons.org/ Cancer Commons] (editor-in-chief, 2011 to the present); [[MedPage Today]] (2010\u20132013); and [[Cureus]] (executive advisor, \u201cMedical Publishing beyond Open Access,\u201d 2014 to the present).\n\nLundberg has been President and Chair of the [http://www.lundberginstitute.org/ Lundberg Institute] from 2009 to the present day. The Lundberg Institute has presented annual lectures in collaboration with the [[Commonwealth Club of California]] in San Francisco since 2012. The purpose of the Lundberg Institute, a non-profit organization, is to forge patient\u2013physician alliances based on trust, providing research, education, leadership, strategies, and communications that promote evidence-informed, efficient, and effective health care delivery to benefit the health and well-being of patients, physicians, and the public.<ref>\u201cThe Lundberg Institute\u201d. Retrieved November 19, 2019.</ref> The not-for-profit 501(c)(3) organization was founded by Lundberg, his spouse and former [[American Society for Clinical Pathology|ASCP]] publisher Patricia Lorimer Lundberg (who remains the CFO), Kathryn Watson (who remains the Secretary), and Peter Jensen (who remains a member of the board of directors).<ref>Lundberg G; Damjanov, I (2020, February 11). \u201cPeer-to-Peer, Featuring George Lundberg\u201d. ''The Pathologist.'' Retrieved April 1, 2020.</ref> The Lundberg Institute is also home to the Curious Dr. George Blog. \n\n== Personal Life ==\nBorn on March 21, 1933 in Pensacola, Florida, George D. Lundberg was the only child of music teacher George David Lundberg and music and first-grade schoolteacher Louise Johnson Lundberg. The Lundbergs were second-generation Swedish (via Chicago) immigrants and pioneer settlers of Silverhill, Alabama.<ref>\"George David Lundberg, M.D.\". Retrieved March 27, 2020.</ref> Young George was gifted intellectually and, from the time he was six years old, he knew he wanted to be a doctor. After brief consideration of a violin career in Chicago, he finished high school (Robertsdale, Alabama) in 1948 at the age of 15, having skipped the 5th, 8th, and 11th grades. Lundberg first married in 1956 (until 1983); from 1983 to the present day he has been married to Patricia Lorimer Lundberg. He has 5 children, 11 grandchildren, and 2 great-grandchildren. When not working, Lundberg reads, hikes, cooks, swims, and is an enthusiast of the visual and performing arts and Alabama football.<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref>\n\n== Major Works ==\n\nAmong other works, Lundberg has written or edited the following:\n\nLundberg, GD (1975). ''Managing the Patient-Focused Laboratory''. Oradell, NJ: Medical Economics Publishing Company. 379 pp.\n\nWoolley, BH, and Lundberg, GD, eds. (1976). ''Pathology for the Practicing Pharmacist.'' Miami: Symposia Specialists Medical Books. 306 pp.\n\nLundberg, GD (1983). ''Using the Clinical Laboratory in Medical Decision Making.'' Chicago: ASCP Press. 327 pp.\n\nCole, HM, and Lundberg, GD, eds. (1986). ''AIDS: From the Beginning''. Chicago: American Medical Association. 441 pp.\n\nMeyer, HS, and Lundberg, GD, eds. (1986). ''Fifty-One Landmark Articles in Medicine: The JAMA Centennial Series.'' Chicago: Chicago Review Press. 486 pp.\n\nSpringer, MD, and Lundberg, GD, eds. (1991). ''\u00a0Caring for the Uninsured and Underinsured: A Compendium From the Specialty Journals of the American Medical Association''. Chicago: American Medical Association.\n\nKoop, CE, and Lundberg, GD, eds. (1992). ''Violence: A Compendium from the Specialty Journals of the American Medical Association''. Chicago: American Medical Association.\n\n== Further Reading ==\n\nLundberg, G; Damjanov, I (2020, February 11). \u201c[https://thepathologist.com/outside-the-lab/peer-to-peer-featuring-george-lundberg Peer-to-Peer, Featuring George Lundberg]\u201d. ''The Pathologist.''\n\nLundberg, GD (2019, May 15). \u201c[https://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/912737#vp_1 The Art and Science of JAMA, Then and Now]\u201d. ''Medscape.''\n\nOwen, D (2003, September). ''[http://sites.rootsweb.com/~alcsilve/lundbergg.html George David Lundberg, M.D].''\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lundberg, George D}}\n\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American pathologists]]\n[[Category:American online publication editors]]\n[[Category:Medical journal editors]]\n\n\n{{US-med-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American pathologist and writer (born 1933)}}\n'''George David Theodore Lundberg''' (born March 21, 1933) is an American [[board certified|board-certified]] [[pathologist]] and writer.<ref>[http://sites.rootsweb.com/~alcsilve/lundbergg.html \"George David Lundberg, M.D.\"]. Retrieved December 08, 2018.</ref> \n\nFor seventeen years, from 1982 to 1999, Lundberg served as editor-in-chief of the ''[[JAMA (journal)|Journal of the American Medical Association]]'' (''JAMA''), followed by a decade (February 1999 to January 2009) as the editor-in-chief of [[Medscape]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Romaine|first=M|last2=Zatz|first2=S|last3=Brown|first3=K|last4=Lundberg|first4=GD|year=2009|title=So long but not farewell: ''The Medscape Journal of Medicine'' (1999-2009)|url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/587141|journal=Medscape Journal of Medicine|volume=11|issue=1|page=33|pmid=19295954|url-access=registration|accessdate=21 February 2009}}</ref> where he has served as [[editor-at-large]] for the site since 2013.<ref>[https://www.medscape.com/author/george-lundberg \"George D. Lundberg, MD\"]. [[Medscape]]. Retrieved December 08, 2018.</ref> Lundberg is president and chair of the [http://www.lundberginstitute.org/ Lundberg Institute], which presents annual lectures in collaboration with the [https://www.commonwealthclub.org/ Commonwealth Club of California] in San Francisco. Lundberg has been elected to the [[National Academy of Medicine]].<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref>\n\nLundberg\u2019s varied career has comprised four phases of roughly equal duration:\n\n(1) Government service (US Army, LTC, [[Vietnam Era]], in Los Angeles),\n\n(2) Full-time academia ([[University of Southern California]] and [[University of California, Davis]]),\n\n(3) Not-for-profit publishing ([[American Medical Association]]), and\n\n(4) For-profit and not-for-profit entrepreneurship: [[Medscape]] from [[WebMD]]; [https://www.medpagetoday.com/ MedPage Today] from [[Everyday Health]]; [https://www.rennovahealth.com/brands/collabrx CollabRx] (chief medical officer and editor-in-chief); [https://www.selfcarecatalysts.com/ Self-Care Catalysts]; [https://www.cancercommons.org/ Cancer Commons] (editor-in-chief); [[Cureus]] (executive advisor); the [http://www.lundberginstitute.org/ Lundberg Institute] (president and board chair); the Curious Dr. George Blog (through the [http://www.lundberginstitute.org/ Lundberg Institute], editor-in-chief); and [https://www.potentiametrics.com/ PotentiaMetrics].\n\nAs of 2020, Lundberg continues his valuable work through several of these same ventures and venues. He has recently acted as consulting professor of pathology and health research and policy at [[Stanford University]], sits on the medical advisory board of Cancer Commons and on the board of visitors at the [[University of Alabama at Birmingham]], and is Clinical Professor of Pathology at [https://www.feinberg.northwestern.edu/ Northwestern University\u2019s Feinberg School of Medicine]. \n\n== Education ==\nLundberg possesses degrees from eight different colleges and universities. First attending college at the age of 15, he received his AA degree in pre-med from [[North Park Junior College]] in Chicago in 1950 and a BS in chemistry from the [[University of Alabama]] in 1952. Beginning his medical work as an operating room janitor and promoted to ward orderly during pre-med, Lundberg obtained his MD from the [[Medical College of Alabama]] in 1957 and performed a rotating clinical internship in Honolulu as part of an 11-year stint in the Regular US Army Medical Corps ([[Vietnam Era]]). His residency, from 1958 to 1962, was in anatomic and clinical pathology at [[Brooke General Hospital]], Fort Sam Houston, Texas; Lundberg\u2019s degrees also include an MS in pathology from [[Baylor University]]. He has held academic professorial appointments from six universities, including [[Harvard University|Harvard]] and [[Stanford University|Stanford]] universities.<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref>\n\n== Career, Professional Life, and Research ==\nDuring his fourth year of medical school, Lundberg voluntarily enlisted in the Army and spent the next 11 years training in and then practicing pathology as a second lieutenant and then lieutenant colonel.<ref>\u201cThe Online Medicine Man\u201d. ''College News'', University of Alabama College of Arts and Sciences. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref> He was on military staff duty at [https://www.nps.gov/prsf/learn/historyculture/letterman-complex.htm Letterman General Hospita]l on the [https://www.presidio.gov/ Presidio of San Francisco] when he first encountered computers in 1963, automating the [http://www.cttr.org/ California Tumor Tissue Registry]. Although never a self-proclaimed \u201ctechie,\u201d he has utilized computers in the practice of medicine from 1963 until today.<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref>\n\nLundberg was chief pathologist as an Lieutenant Colonel at [[William Beaumont General Hospital]] in El Paso from 1964 to 1967, placing computers into the clinical laboratory as a pioneer early adopter in 1966. Although Lundberg stated that \u201cthe Army treated me very well,\u201d he and his wife had three young children and \u201cthey kept making me move around,\u201d so he chose to leave the Army, becoming Associate Professor of Pathology at the [[University of Southern California]] in Los Angeles in 1967.<ref>\u201cThe Online Medicine Man\u201d. ''College News'', University of Alabama College of Arts and Sciences. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref> There, Lundberg focused on research and teaching on drug-induced diseases. Promoted to Assistant Director of Laboratories and Pathology at the [[Los Angeles County \u2013 USC Medical Center|Los Angeles County\u2013USC Medical Center]] in 1968 (and later becoming Associate Director in 1972), he led the growth of this department to become the world\u2019s largest and most productive hospital laboratory between 1968 and 1977. In 1969, Lundberg placed computers into the clinical laboratory while concurrently abolishing the \u201cration stamp\u201d approach to controlling excess lab test use.<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref><ref>\u201cThe Online Medicine Man\u201d. ''College News'', University of Alabama College of Arts and Sciences. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref>\n\nLeveraging the tragic 1969 death of American media personality [[Diane Linkletter|Art Linkletter\u2019s daughter Diane]], Lundberg obtained Los Angeles County funding to build and maintain a 24/7 hospital clinical toxicology lab that became a model for the field. As part of this process, Lundberg's group invented (and was credited with) and implemented the [https://www.legacyhealth.org/for-health-professionals/refer-a-patient/laboratory-services/critical-values-and-reference-ranges.aspx critical laboratory value] system, a system that quickly became (and remains) the standard of hospital laboratory practice all over the world.<ref>Lippi, G; Mattiuzi, C (2016, October). \u201cCritical laboratory values communications: summary recommendations from available guidelines\u201d. ''Annals of Translational Medicine.'' '''4''' (20): 400. doi:10.21037/atm.2016.09.36. Retrieved March 29, 2020.</ref><ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref> The term \u201ccritical laboratory value,\u201d also known as critical result, panic value, or alert value, was defined by Lundberg himself in 1972 as a result that represents a pathophysiological state different from normal, one that poses risk to a patient's life unless an immediate action is taken.<ref>Rocha, BCB; Alves, JAR; Pinto, FPD; Mendes, ME; Sumita, NM (2016). \u201cThe critical value concept in clinical laboratory\u201d. ''Brazilian Journal of Pathology and Laboratory Medicine.'' '''52''' (1). Retrieved March 28, 2020.</ref><ref>Lundberg G (1972). \u201cWhen to panic over an abnormal value\u201d. ''Medical Laboratory Observer.'' '''4''': 47\u201354.</ref>\n\nBy the early 1970s, the Los Angeles County emergency room was seeing 50 to 70 patients a day with illnesses suspected to be drug related.<ref>Lundberg, GD; Wahlberg, CB; Pantlik, VA (1974). \u201cFrequency of clinical toxicology test-ordering (primarily overdose cases) and results in a large urban general hospital\u201d. ''Clinical Chemistry''. '''20''' (2): 121\u20135. Retrieved March 27, 2020.</ref> Lundberg responded to the street drug epidemic by establishing a \u201cStreet Drug Identification Program\u201d so that users could learn the real identity of the substances they were buying; he publicized this information through a weekly Dope Scoreboard in the Los Angeles Free Press.<ref>Lundberg, GD; Gupta, RC; Montgomery, S (1974, April 1). \u201cA Street Drug Identification Program\u201d. ''Laboratory Medicine.'' '''5''' (4): 8\u201310. doi.org/10.1093/labmed/5.4.8. Retrieved March 27, 2020.</ref> In the mid-1970s, Lundberg invented the patient-focused (now termed \u201cpatient-centered\u201d) approach to laboratory medicine, organizing the laboratory around turnaround times for analytical test performance needed to make appropriate and timely clinical decisions.<ref>Benson, ES (1977, January 3). \u201cManaging the Patient-Focused Laboratory\u201d. ''JAMA.'' '''237''' (1): 69. doi:10.1001/jama.1977.03270280071032. Retrieved March 27, 2020.</ref><ref>Lundberg, GD (1975). ''Managing the Patient-Focused Laboratory''. Oradell, NJ: Medical Economics Publishing Company. 379 pp.</ref>\n\nIn 1977 Lundberg became Professor and Chair of Pathology at [[UC Davis School of Medicine]]. Here, with others, in 1980 he revised an entire 4-year medical school curriculum using a modified Delphi approach, implementing it in less than one year, with student achievement outcome measures set and accomplished.<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref>\n\n===''JAMA''===\nFor 20 years, Lundberg had practiced pathology in hospitals, in academia, and in the military, but in 1982, he received an offer that propelled him in a new direction, one that led him to a new kind of medical pioneering. Lundberg had been sitting on the ''[[JAMA (journal)|Journal of the American Medical Association]]''\u2019s (''JAMA'') editorial board since 1974 and even started his own column for the journal. By 1981, however, the [[American Medical Association]] wanted a new editor-in-chief, and Lundberg was their first choice.<ref>\u201cThe Online Medicine Man\u201d. ''College News'', University of Alabama College of Arts and Sciences. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref>\n\nAs editor-in-chief, Lundberg had editorial responsibility for all 10 [[American Medical Association|AMA]] specialty journals. He also created the concept of \u201ctheme issues\u201d for the journal to achieve a host of editorial and public health/policy objectives, in which the editorial team selected relevant papers based on topics that were of particular interest to readers. Such issues covered topics like prevention of nuclear war, alternative medicine, Hispanic and African American health, boxing, guns and violence, women\u2019s health, caring for the uninsured, alcohol, and tobacco.<ref>Lundberg, GD (2019, May 15). \u201cThe Art and Science of JAMA, Then and Now\u201d. ''Medscape.'' Retrieved March 28, 2020.</ref> \u201cI think we published eight or nine tobacco-themed issues over the years, and those publications are credited with being central to the movement of stopping tobacco smoking for most of America,\u201d Lundberg said. \u201cThat was hugely important.\u201d<ref>\u201cThe Online Medicine Man\u201d. ''College News'', University of Alabama College of Arts and Sciences. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref><ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref> Lundberg also began a series in ''JAMA'', \u201cToward Optimal Laboratory Use,\u201d that introduced the physicians of the world to algorithms (this series ran for 30 years) and also resulted in the book ''Using the Clinical Laboratory in Medical Decision Making''.<ref>Lundberg, GD (1983). ''Using the Clinical Laboratory in Medical Decision Making.'' Chicago: ASCP Press. 327 pp.</ref>\n\nIn 1987 Lundberg established peer review as a \u201cscience\u201d though the quadrennial International Congress on Peer Review in Biomedical Publication. Lundberg hosted medical television education programs on cable television; he achieved high visibility in the public media through his consideration of public journalists as colleagues who could help to educate the public about important advances in medical and health knowledge. And he involved promising medical students in becoming medical editors, with prominent alumni of this program including Drs [[Erica Frank]], [[Scott Gottlieb]], and [https://retractionwatch.com/meet-the-retraction-watch-staff/about/ Ivan Oransky]. With others at [https://wame.org/report-of-the-bellagio-conference Bellagio in 1995], Lundberg created the [[World Association of Medical Editors]] (WAME).<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref>\n\nIn 1999 Lundberg was fired from his position at ''JAMA'' after the publishing of a controversial article on how college students define [[oral sex]]<ref>Sanders, SA; Reinisch, JM (1999, January 20). \u201cWould You Say You \u2018Had Sex\u2019 If \u2026 ?\u201d ''JAMA.'' '''281''' (3): 275\u20137. doi:10.1001/jama.281.3.275. Retrieved March 27, 2020.</ref>; the article coincided with related issues in U.S. [[Impeachment of Bill Clinton|President Clinton's impeachment trial]].<ref>\"Editor Fired Over Sex Article\". [[CBS News]]. Retrieved December 08, 2018.</ref> Executives from the [[American Medical Association]], stating that the article had nothing to do with medicine and that it jeopardized the high standard of the journal, attempted to prevent publication, but failed.<ref>\"Health Editor fired over oral sex story\". [[BBC News]]. Retrieved December 08, 2018.</ref><ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref> Longtime observers of medicine criticized the firing, saying good journals often speed publication of articles relevant to public health or public debate: \u201cI think this is a tragedy, since George Lundberg is a giant in the field of American medical publishing, and under his leadership, the journal flourished,\u201d said [[Arthur Caplan]], director of bioethics at the [[University of Pennsylvania]]; [[June Reinisch|June M. Reinisch]], co-author of the article in the January 20 issue of ''JAMA'', said she was \u201cabsolutely shocked\u201d by the firing and that there had been nothing unusual about ''JAMA''\u2019s handling of the article.<ref>Coleman, BC (1999, January 15). \u201c''JAMA'' Editor Fired Over Sex Article\u201d. ''AP News.'' Retrieved November 21, 2019.</ref>\n\nBy the time Lundberg left ''JAMA'' in 1999, he\u2019d helped to run and create 21 international editions in 13 languages\u2014covering everywhere from Moscow to Buenos Aires. He had doubled the worldwide circulation of the print ''JAMA'' to the world\u2019s largest print circulation of any general medical journal and increased the JAMA SCI Impact factor from about 4 to nearly 20.<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref><ref>\u201cThe Online Medicine Man\u201d. ''College News'', University of Alabama College of Arts and Sciences. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref>\n\n=== The Online Medicine Man <ref>The title of this section reflects the title of the following article: \u201cThe Online Medicine Man\u201d. ''College News'', University of Alabama College of Arts and Sciences. Retrieved July 29, 2019.</ref>===\nLundberg, along with a few other pioneers, invented \u201cInternet Medicine\u201d in the late 1990s. From 1999 to 2009 and again in 2013\u20132019, Lundberg was the editor of ''[[Medscape]]'' (from [[WebMD]]), where he currently serves as editor-at-large for the site. During a 2001\u20132002 timeframe, Lundberg invented the concurrent triple medium (\u201cread, listen, watch, all on the same page\u201d) video editorial, and continues to publish such regularly.<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref>\n\nLundberg\u2019s additional and notable online medical presence includes [[CollabRx]] (chief medical officer and editor-in-chief, 2010\u20132018); the precision oncology of [https://www.cancercommons.org/ Cancer Commons] (editor-in-chief, 2011 to the present); [[MedPage Today]] (2010\u20132013); and [[Cureus]] (executive advisor, \u201cMedical Publishing beyond Open Access,\u201d 2014 to the present).\n\nLundberg has been President and Chair of the [http://www.lundberginstitute.org/ Lundberg Institute] from 2009 to the present day. The Lundberg Institute has presented annual lectures in collaboration with the [[Commonwealth Club of California]] in San Francisco since 2012. The purpose of the Lundberg Institute, a non-profit organization, is to forge patient\u2013physician alliances based on trust, providing research, education, leadership, strategies, and communications that promote evidence-informed, efficient, and effective health care delivery to benefit the health and well-being of patients, physicians, and the public.<ref>\u201cThe Lundberg Institute\u201d. Retrieved November 19, 2019.</ref> The not-for-profit 501(c)(3) organization was founded by Lundberg, his spouse and former [[American Society for Clinical Pathology|ASCP]] publisher Patricia Lorimer Lundberg (who remains the CFO), Kathryn Watson (who remains the Secretary), and Peter Jensen (who remains a member of the board of directors).<ref>Lundberg G; Damjanov, I (2020, February 11). \u201cPeer-to-Peer, Featuring George Lundberg\u201d. ''The Pathologist.'' Retrieved April 1, 2020.</ref> The Lundberg Institute is also home to the Curious Dr. George Blog. \n\n== Personal Life ==\nBorn on March 21, 1933 in Pensacola, Florida, George D. Lundberg was the only child of music teacher George David Lundberg and music and first-grade schoolteacher Louise Johnson Lundberg. The Lundbergs were second-generation Swedish (via Chicago) immigrants and pioneer settlers of Silverhill, Alabama.<ref>\"George David Lundberg, M.D.\". Retrieved March 27, 2020.</ref> Young George was gifted intellectually and, from the time he was six years old, he knew he wanted to be a doctor. After brief consideration of a violin career in Chicago, he finished high school (Robertsdale, Alabama) in 1948 at the age of 15, having skipped the 5th, 8th, and 11th grades. Lundberg first married in 1956 (until 1983); from 1983 to the present day he has been married to Patricia Lorimer Lundberg. He has 5 children, 11 grandchildren, and 2 great-grandchildren. When not working, Lundberg reads, hikes, cooks, swims, and is an enthusiast of the visual and performing arts and Alabama football.<ref>Lundberg, George. Interviews by Debora Holmes. Email correspondence. June 2019\u2013January 2020.</ref>\n\n== Major Works ==\n\nAmong other works, Lundberg has written or edited the following:\n\nLundberg, GD (1975). ''Managing the Patient-Focused Laboratory''. Oradell, NJ: Medical Economics Publishing Company. 379 pp.\n\nWoolley, BH, and Lundberg, GD, eds. (1976). ''Pathology for the Practicing Pharmacist.'' Miami: Symposia Specialists Medical Books. 306 pp.\n\nLundberg, GD (1983). ''Using the Clinical Laboratory in Medical Decision Making.'' Chicago: ASCP Press. 327 pp.\n\nCole, HM, and Lundberg, GD, eds. (1986). ''AIDS: From the Beginning''. Chicago: American Medical Association. 441 pp.\n\nMeyer, HS, and Lundberg, GD, eds. (1986). ''Fifty-One Landmark Articles in Medicine: The JAMA Centennial Series.'' Chicago: Chicago Review Press. 486 pp.\n\nSpringer, MD, and Lundberg, GD, eds. (1991). ''\u00a0Caring for the Uninsured and Underinsured: A Compendium From the Specialty Journals of the American Medical Association''. Chicago: American Medical Association.\n\nKoop, CE, and Lundberg, GD, eds. (1992). ''Violence: A Compendium from the Specialty Journals of the American Medical Association''. Chicago: American Medical Association.\n\n== Further Reading ==\n\nLundberg, G; Damjanov, I (2020, February 11). \u201cPeer-to-Peer, Featuring George Lundberg\u201d. ''The Pathologist.''\n\nLundberg, GD (2019, May 15). \u201cThe Art and Science of JAMA, Then and Now\u201d. ''Medscape.''\n\nOwen, D (2003, September). ''George David Lundberg, M.D.''\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lundberg, George D}}\n\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American pathologists]]\n[[Category:American online publication editors]]\n[[Category:Medical journal editors]]\n\n\n{{US-med-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Debora Holmes", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Provided links.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_D._Lundberg"}
{"title_page": "Derek Jacobi", "text_new": "{{short description|British actor and film director}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| caption      = Jacobi in 2013\n| honorific_prefix = [[Sir]]\n| name         = Derek Jacobi\n| honorific_suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100|CBE}}\n| image        = Derek Jacobi 2013.jpg\n| imagesize    = \n| birth_name   = Derek George Jacobi\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1938|10|22}}\n| birth_place  = [[Leytonstone]], [[Essex]]<!-- Do not change to London, Leytonstone was in Essex in 1938-->, England\n| alma_mater   = [[St John's College, Cambridge]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| occupation   = Actor, director\n| years_active = 1961\u2013present\n| partner      = Richard Clifford (1979\u2013present)\n}}\n'''Sir Derek George Jacobi''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d\u0292|\u00e6|k|\u0259|b|i}}; born 22 October 1938) is an English actor and stage director.\n\nA \"forceful, commanding stage presence\",<ref name=britannica>{{cite web| title =Jacobi, Sir Derek| work=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica's Guide to Shakespeare| publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.]]| year=2008| url=http://www.britannica.com/shakespeare/article-9343265| accessdate=4 April 2008}}</ref> Jacobi has enjoyed a successful stage career, appearing in such stage productions as ''[[Hamlet]]'',<ref name=\"Wheatley\">{{cite news |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article5356211.ece |work=[[The Times]] |location=London |title=First knight of nerves for Derek Jacobi and A Bunch of Amateurs |first=Jane |last=Wheatley |date=18 December 2008 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> ''[[Uncle Vanya]]'',<ref name=\"ibdb.com\">{{cite web| url=http://www.ibdb.com/person.php?id=46744| title=Derek Jacobi Credits, Broadway| publisher=[[Internet Broadway Database]]|  accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref> and ''[[Oedipus Rex|Oedipus the King]]''. He has twice been awarded a [[Laurence Olivier Award]], first for his performance of the eponymous hero in ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' in 1983 and the second for his Malvolio in ''[[Twelfth Night]]'' in 2009. He also received a [[Tony Award]] for his performance in ''[[Much Ado About Nothing]]'' in 1984 and a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or a Movie|Primetime Emmy Award]] in 1988 for ''[[The Tenth Man (1988 film)|The Tenth Man]]''. His stage work includes playing [[Antony and Cleopatra|Octavius Caesar]], [[Edward II (play)|Edward&nbsp;II]], [[Richard III (play)|Richard III]]<ref name=\"filmreference.com\">{{cite web| url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/93/Derek-Jacobi.html| title=Derek Jacobi Biography| publisher=FilmReference.com| accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref> and [[Becket|Thomas Becket]].\n\nIn addition to being a founder member of the [[Royal National Theatre]] and winning several prestigious theatre awards, Jacobi has also enjoyed a successful television career, starring in the critically praised<ref name=\"Wheatley\"/> adaptation of [[Robert Graves]]'s ''[[I, Claudius (TV series)|I, Claudius]]'' (1976), for which he won a [[BAFTA]]; in the titular role in the medieval drama series ''[[Cadfael (TV series)|Cadfael]]'' (1994\u20131998),<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/9359513/Derek-Jacobi-I-dont-mind-people-having-faith.-But-it-aint-for-me.html |title=Derek Jacobi: 'I don\u2019t mind people having faith. But it ain\u2019t for me\u2019 |website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |last=Farndale |first=Nigel |authorlink=Nigel Farndale |date=2 July 2012 |accessdate=24 August 2015}}</ref> as [[Stanley Baldwin]] in ''[[The Gathering Storm (2002 film)|The Gathering Storm]]'' (2002), as Stuart Bixby in the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] comedy ''[[Vicious (TV series)|Vicious]]'' (2013\u20132016) and as Alan Buttershaw in ''[[Last Tango in Halifax]]'' (2012\u2013present). Jacobi also portrayed a version of [[The Master (Doctor Who)|the Master]] in the long running science fiction series ''[[Doctor Who]]''. He later reprised the role for several ''Doctor Who audio dramas'' for [[Big Finish Productions]]\n\nThough principally a stage actor, Jacobi has appeared in a number of films, including ''[[The Day of the Jackal (film)|The Day of the Jackal]]'' (1973), ''[[Henry V (1989 film)|Henry V]]'' (1989), ''[[Dead Again]]'' (1991), ''[[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]]'' (2000), ''[[Gosford Park]]'' (2001), ''[[The Riddle (film)|The Riddle]]'' (2007), ''[[The King's Speech]]'' (2010), ''[[My Week with Marilyn]]'' (2011), ''[[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|Cinderella]]'' (2015), and ''[[Murder on the Orient Express (2017 film)|Murder on the Orient Express]]'' (2017).\n\nHe was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1994<ref>Sarah Stanton, Martin Banham, ''The Cambridge Paperback Guide to Theatre'' (1996), p. 181</ref> and has also been made a member of the Danish [[Order of the Dannebrog]].\n\n==Early life==\nJacobi, an only child, was born in [[Leytonstone]], Essex<!-- Do not change to London, Leytonstone was in Essex in 1938-->, England, the son of Daisy Gertrude (n\u00e9e Masters; 1910\u20131980), a secretary who worked in a [[drapery]] store in Leyton High Road, and Alfred George Jacobi (1910\u20131993), who ran a sweet shop and was a [[tobacconist]] in [[Chingford]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Derek Jacobi Biography (1938\u2013)| url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/93/Derek-Jacobi.html| work=filmreference| year=2008| accessdate=4 April 2008}}</ref> His patrilineal great-grandfather had emigrated from Germany to England during the 19th century. He also has a distant [[Huguenots|Huguenot]] ancestor.<ref>{{cite news| title=Trace your French \u00e9migr\u00e9 ancestors like Sir Derek Jacobi| url=http://www.whodoyouthinkyouaremagazine.com/trace-your-french-%C3%A9migr%C3%A9-ancestors-sir-derek-jacobi| work=[[Who do you think you are magazine]]|date=27 August 2015 | accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| first=Jasper| last=Rees| title=Crown him with many crowns| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2002/07/16/btjaco14.xml&sSheet=/arts/2002/07/20/ixstagetop.html| work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]| location=London| date=15 July 2002| accessdate=4 April 2008}}</ref> His family was working-class,<ref>{{cite news| first=Sally| last=Vincent| title=I already knew I was a tetchy beast| url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/features/story/0,,1875816,00.htm| work=[[The Guardian]]| location=London| date=19 September 2006| accessdate=4 April 2008 }}</ref> and Jacobi describes his childhood as happy. In his teens he went to Leyton County High School for Boys, now known as the [[Leyton Sixth Form College]], and became an integral part of the drama club, The Players of [[Leyton]].\n\nWhile in the [[sixth form]], he starred in a production of ''[[Hamlet]],'' which was taken to the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] and very well regarded.<ref>{{cite news| last=Wheatley| first=Jane| url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article5356211.ece| title=First knight of nerves for Derek Jacobi and A Bunch of Amateurs| work=The Times| date=18 December 2008}}</ref> At 18 he won a scholarship to the [[University of Cambridge]], where he read history at [[St John's College, Cambridge|St John's College]] and earned his degree. Younger members of the university at the time included [[Ian McKellen]] (who had a crush on him\u2014\"a passion that was undeclared and unrequited\", as McKellen relates it)<ref name=\"advocate-2001\">{{cite news| last=Steele| first=Bruce C.| title=The Knight's Crusade: playing the wizard Gandalf in The Lord of the Rings may make Sir Ian McKellen the world's best-known gay man. And he's armed and ready to carry the fight for equality along with him| url=https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-83451265/the-knight-s-crusade-playing-the-wizard-gandalf-in| work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]| date=11 December 2001| pages=36\u201338, 40\u201345}}</ref> and [[Trevor Nunn]]. During his studies at Cambridge, Jacobi played many parts including ''[[Hamlet]]'', which was taken on a tour to Switzerland, where he met [[Richard Burton]]. As a result of his performance of ''[[Edward II (play)|Edward II]]'' at Cambridge, Jacobi was invited to become a member of the [[Birmingham Repertory Theatre]] immediately upon his graduation in 1960.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early work===\nJacobi's talent was recognised by [[Laurence Olivier]], who invited the young actor back to London to become one of the founding members of the new [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]], even though at the time Jacobi was relatively unknown. He played [[Laertes (Hamlet)|Laertes]] in the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre's]] inaugural production of ''[[Hamlet]]'' opposite [[Peter O'Toole]] in 1963. Olivier cast him as [[Michael Cassio|Cassio]] in the successful National Theatre stage production of ''[[Othello]]'', a role that Jacobi repeated in the [[Othello (1965 British film)|1965 film version]]. He played Andrei in the NT production and film of ''[[Three Sisters (1970 Olivier film)|Three Sisters]]'' (1970), both featuring Olivier. On 27 July 1965, Jacobi played Brindsley Miller in the first production of [[Peter Shaffer]]'s ''[[Black Comedy]]''. It was presented by the National Theatre at Chichester and subsequently in London.\n\nAfter eight years at the National Theatre, Jacobi left in 1971 to pursue different roles. In 1972, he starred in the [[BBC]] serial ''Man of Straw'', an adaptation of [[Heinrich Mann]]'s book ''[[Der Untertan]]'', directed by [[Herbert Wise]]. Most of his theatrical work in the 1970s was with the touring classical [[Prospect Theatre Company]], with which he undertook many roles, including ''[[Ivanov (play)|Ivanov]]'', ''[[Pericles, Prince of Tyre]]'' and ''[[A Month in the Country (play)|A Month in the Country]]'' opposite [[Dorothy Tutin]] (1976).\n\nJacobi was increasingly busy with stage and screen acting, but his big breakthrough came in 1976 when he played the title role in the BBC's series ''[[I, Claudius (TV series)|I, Claudius]]''. He cemented his reputation with his performance as the stammering, twitching [[Claudius|Emperor Claudius]], winning much praise. In 1979, thanks to his international popularity, he took ''[[Hamlet]]'' on a theatrical world tour through England, [[Egypt]], Greece, Sweden, Australia, Japan and China, playing [[Prince Hamlet]]. He was invited to perform the role at [[Kronborg|Kronborg Castle]], Denmark, known as Elsinore Castle, the setting of the play. In 1978, he appeared in the [[BBC Television Shakespeare]] production of ''[[Richard II (play)|Richard II]]'', with Sir [[John Gielgud]] and Dame [[Wendy Hiller]].\n\n===Later career===\nIn 1980, Jacobi took the leading role in the BBC's ''[[Hamlet]]'', made his Broadway debut in ''[[The Suicide (play)|The Suicide]]'' (a run shortened by Jacobi's return home to England due to the death of his mother), and joined the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] (RSC). From 1982 to 1985, he played four demanding roles simultaneously: Benedick in Shakespeare's ''[[Much Ado About Nothing]]'', for which he won a Tony for its Broadway run (1984\u20131985); Prospero in ''[[The Tempest]]''; ''[[Peer Gynt]]''; and ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' which he brought to the US and played in repertory with ''[[Much Ado About Nothing]]'' on Broadway and in Washington DC (1984\u20131985). In 1986, he made his West End debut in ''[[Breaking the Code]]'' by [[Hugh Whitemore]], starring in the role of [[Alan Turing]], which was written with Jacobi specifically in mind. The play was taken to Broadway. In 1988, Jacobi alternated in West End the title roles of Shakespeare's ''[[Richard II (play)|Richard II]]'' and ''[[Richard III (play)|Richard III]]'' in repertoire.\n\nHe appeared in the television dramas ''[[Inside the Third Reich (film)|Inside the Third Reich]]'' (1982), where he played [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]]; ''[[Mr Pye]]'' (1985); and ''[[Little Dorrit (1987 film)|Little Dorrit]]'' (1987), based on [[Charles Dickens]]'s novel; ''[[The Tenth Man (1988 film)|The Tenth Man]]'' (1988) with [[Anthony Hopkins]] and [[Kristin Scott Thomas]]. In 1982, he lent his voice to the character of Nicodemus in the animated film, ''[[The Secret of NIMH]]''. In 1990, he starred as [[Daedalus]] in episode 4 of ''[[Jim Henson's The Storyteller: Greek Myths]]''.\n\nJacobi continued to play Shakespeare roles, notably in [[Kenneth Branagh]]'s 1989 film of ''[[Henry V (1989 film)|Henry V]]'' (as [[Greek chorus|the Chorus]]), and made his directing debut as Branagh's director for the 1988 [[Renaissance Theatre Company]]'s touring production of ''[[Hamlet]]'', which also played at [[Helsing\u00f8r|Elsinore]] and as part of a Renaissance repertory season at the [[Phoenix Theatre (London)|Phoenix Theatre]] in London. The 1990s saw Jacobi keeping on with repertoire stage work in ''Kean'' at the [[Old Vic]], ''[[Becket]]'' in the West End (the [[Haymarket Theatre]]) and ''[[Macbeth]]'' at the RSC in both London and [[Stratford-upon-Avon|Stratford]]. In 1993 Jacobi voiced Mr Jeremy Fisher in ''[[The World of Peter Rabbit and Friends]]''.\n\nHe was appointed the joint [[artistic director]] of the [[Chichester Festival Theatre]], with the West End impresario Duncan Weldon in 1995 for a three-year tenure. As an actor at Chichester he also starred in four plays, including his first ''[[Uncle Vanya]]'' in 1996 (he played it again in 2000, bringing the [[Anton Chekhov|Chekhov]] play to Broadway for a limited run). Jacobi's work during the 1990s included the 13-episode series TV adaptation of the novels by [[Edith Pargeter|Ellis Peters]], ''[[Cadfael (TV series)|Cadfael]]'' (1994\u20131998) and a televised version of ''Breaking the Code'' (1996). Film appearances of the era included performances in [[Kenneth Branagh]]'s ''[[Dead Again]]'' (1991), Branagh's full-text rendition of ''[[Hamlet (1996 film)|Hamlet]]'' (1996) as [[King Claudius]], [[John Maybury]]'s ''[[Love Is the Devil: Study for a Portrait of Francis Bacon|Love is the Devil]]'' (1998), a portrait of painter [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]], as Senator Gracchus in ''[[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]]'' (2000) with [[Russell Crowe]], and as \"The Duke\" opposite [[Christopher Eccleston]] and [[Eddie Izzard]] in a post-[[apocalypse|apocalyptic]] version of [[Thomas Middleton]]'s ''[[The Revenger's Tragedy]]'' (2002).\n\nIn 2001, Jacobi won an [[Emmy Award]]<ref>{{cite news| first=Duncan| last=Campbell| title=TV stars dress down for the Emmy awards| url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/nov/06/broadcasting.internationalnews| work=[[The Guardian]]| location=| date=6 November 2001| accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref> by mocking his Shakespearean background in the television sitcom ''[[Frasier]]'' episode \"[[Frasier (season 8)|The Show Must Go Off]]\", in which he played the world's ''worst'' Shakespearean actor: the hammy, loud, untalented Jackson Hedley. This was his first guest appearance on an American television programme.\n\n===2000\u2013present===\nJacobi has narrated audio book versions of the ''[[Iliad]]'', ''[[The Voyage of the Dawn Treader]]'' by [[C. S. Lewis]], ''[[Farmer Giles of Ham]]'' by [[J. R. R. Tolkien]], and two abridged versions of ''[[I, Claudius]]'' by [[Robert Graves]]. In 2001, he provided the voice of \"Duke Theseus\" in ''The Children's Midsummer Night's Dream'' film. In 2002, Jacobi toured Australia in ''[[The Hollow Crown (TV series)|The Hollow Crown]]'' with Sir [[Donald Sinden]], [[Ian Richardson]] and Dame [[Diana Rigg]]. Jacobi also played the role of Senator Gracchus in [[Gladiator (2000 film)|''Gladiator'']] and starred in the 2002 miniseries ''[[The Jury (TV serial)|The Jury]]''. He is also the narrator for the BBC children's series ''[[In the Night Garden...]]''.\n\nIn 2003, he was involved with ''[[Scream of the Shalka]]'', a [[webcast]] based on the science fiction series ''[[Doctor Who]]''. He played the voice of the Doctor's nemesis [[Master (Doctor Who)|the Master]] alongside [[Richard E. Grant]] as [[Doctor (Doctor Who)|the Doctor]]. In the same year, he also appeared in ''[[Deadline (audio drama)|Deadline]]'', an audio drama also based on ''Doctor Who''. Therein he played Martin Bannister, an ageing writer who makes up stories about \"the Doctor\", a character who travels in time and space, the premise being that the series had never made it on to television. Jacobi later followed this up with an appearance in the ''Doctor Who'' episode \"[[Utopia (Doctor Who)|Utopia]]\" (June 2007); he appears as the kindly Professor Yana, who by the end of the episode is revealed to actually be the Master. Jacobi admitted to ''[[Doctor Who Confidential]]'' he had always wanted to be on the show: \"One of my ambitions since the '60s has been to take part in a ''Doctor Who''. The other one is ''[[Coronation Street]]''. So I've cracked ''Doctor Who'' now. I'm still waiting for ''Corrie''.\"<ref>{{cite episode| serieslink=Doctor Who Confidential#Series 3 .282007.29| series=Doctor Who| network=BBC| season=3| number=40| title='Ello, 'Ello, 'Ello}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Jacobi starred in [[Friedrich Schiller]]'s ''[[Don Carlos (play)|Don Carlos]]'' at the [[Crucible Theatre]] in [[Sheffield]], in an acclaimed production, which transferred to the [[Gielgud Theatre]] in London in January 2005. The London production of ''Don Carlos'' gathered rave reviews. Also in 2004, he starred as Lord Teddy Thursby in the first of the four-part BBC series ''[[Jake Arnott|The Long Firm]]'', based on [[Jake Arnott]]'s novel of the same name. In ''[[Nanny McPhee]]'' (2005), he played the role of the colourful Mr. Wheen, an undertaker. He played the role of [[Alexander Corvinus]] in the 2006 movie ''[[Underworld: Evolution]]''.\n\nIn March 2006, [[BBC Two]] broadcast ''[[Pinochet in Suburbia]]'', a [[docudrama]] about former [[Chile]]an dictator [[Augusto Pinochet]] and the attempts to [[extradition|extradite]] him from Great Britain; Jacobi played the leading role. In September 2007, it was released in the U.S., retitled ''Pinochet's Last Stand''. In 2006, he appeared in the children's movie ''Mist'', the tale of a sheepdog puppy, he also narrated this movie. In July\u2013August 2006, he played the eponymous role in ''[[A Voyage Round My Father]]'' at the [[Donmar Warehouse]], a production which then transferred to the West End.\n[[Image:Derek Jacobi-autograph.jpg|thumb|Jacobi signing autographs after his performance in ''[[Twelfth Night]]'', London, 2009]]\nIn February 2007, ''[[The Riddle (film)|The Riddle]]'', directed by [[Brendan Foley]] and starring Jacobi, [[Vinnie Jones]], and [[Vanessa Redgrave]], was screened at Berlin EFM. Jacobi plays twin roles: first a present-day London tramp and then the ghost of [[Charles Dickens]]. In March 2007, the BBC's children's programme ''[[In the Night Garden...]]'' started its run of one hundred episodes, with Jacobi as the narrator. He played Nell's grandfather in ITV's Christmas 2007 adaptation of ''[[The Old Curiosity Shop]]'', and returned to the stage to play Malvolio in Shakespeare's ''[[Twelfth Night]]'' (2009) for the Donmar Warehouse at [[Wyndham's Theatre]] in London.<ref>{{cite journal| last=Billings| first=Joshua| url=http://www.oxonianreview.org/wp/star-crossed| title=Star-Crossed| work=[[Oxonian Review]]| issue=8.3| date=9 February 2009}}</ref> The role won him the [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor]].<ref>{{cite news| date=9 March 2009| url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/gallery/2009/mar/09/olivier-awards-theatre| title=Olivier awards 2009: the winners| publisher=WhatsonStage.com| accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref> He appears in five 2009 films: ''[[Morris: A Life with Bells On]]'', ''[[Hippie Hippie Shake]]'', ''[[Endgame (2009 film)|Endgame]]'', ''[[Adam Resurrected]]'' and [[Charles Dickens's England]]. In 2010, he returned to ''I, Claudius'', as Augustus in a [[I, Claudius (radio adaptation)|radio adaptation]]. In 2011, he was part of a medieval epic, ''[[Ironclad (film)|Ironclad]]'', which also starred James Purefoy and Paul Giamatti, as the ineffectual Reginald de Cornhill, castellan of Rochester castle.\n\nJacobi starred in [[Michael Grandage]]'s production of ''[[King Lear]]'' (London, 2010), giving what ''[[The New Yorker]]'' called \"one of the finest performances of his distinguished career\".<ref>{{cite journal| last=Lahr| first=John| authorlink=John Lahr|title=Crazy Love| journal=The New Yorker| date=3 January 2011| pages=74\u201375| url=https://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/theatre/2011/01/03/110103crth_theatre_lahr| accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref> In May 2011, he reprised this role at the [[Brooklyn Academy of Music]].<ref>{{cite news| first=Ben| last=Brantley| date=5 May 2011| url=http://theater.nytimes.com/2011/05/07/theater/reviews/king-lear-with-derek-jacobi-at-bam-review.html?| title=Fantasies Aside, Life\u2019s Tough At the Top| work=[[The New York Times]]| accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2012, he appeared in ''[[Titanic: Blood and Steel]]'' and in November 2012, he starred in the BBC series ''[[Last Tango in Halifax]]''. In 2013, he starred in the second series of ''Last Tango'', and in 2014, the third series.\n\nIn 2013, Jacobi starred alongside [[Ian McKellen]] in the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] sitcom ''[[Vicious (TV series)|Vicious]]'' as Stuart Bixby, the partner to Freddie Thornhill, played by McKellen. On 23 August 2013 the show was renewed for a six-episode second series which began airing in June 2015.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a509391/vicious-renewed-for-second-series-by-itv-job-lot-moving-to-itv2.html| title='Vicious' renewed for second series by ITV, 'Job Lot' moving to ITV2| work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=23 August 2013| accessdate=7 September 2013}}</ref> The show ended in December 2016, with a Christmas special.\n\nSince 2017, Jacobi has again portrayed The Master in several box set series for [[Big Finish Productions]], collectively entitled [[The War Master (audio drama series)|\"The War Master\"]].\n\nIn 2018, he played the Bishop of Digne in the BBC miniseries ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (2018 miniseries)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]]''.\n\n==Shakespeare authorship involvement==\n[[Image:00 poslednik derek pijarowski 20181126.jpg|thumb|R. Poslednik, D. Jacobi & [[Jaroslaw Pijarowski]] with World United Creator \u2013 Platinum Demiurge Award for his contribution to uniting and promoting world literature based on his efforts to introduce William Shakespeare into modern cinema, London, 2018]]\nJacobi has been publicly involved in the [[Shakespeare authorship question]]. He supports the [[Oxfordian theory of Shakespeare authorship]], according to which [[Edward de Vere, 17th Earl of Oxford]] wrote the works of Shakespeare.<ref>{{cite news| last=Thorpe| first=Vanessa| url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/sep/09/theatrenews.theatre| title=Who Was Shakespeare? That Is (Still) the Question: Campaign Revives Controversy of Bard's Identity| work=[[The Observer]]| date=9 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last=Horwitz| first=Jane| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/08/AR2010060804593.html| title=Backstage: What the Stars Had to Get Over to Get their 'Goat' on at Rep Stage| work=[[The Washington Post]]| date=9 June 2010|ref=harv}}</ref> Jacobi <!--is a patron of the [[De Vere Society]],<ref name=\"deveresociety\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deveresociety.co.uk/index.html|publisher=deveresociety.co.uk|title=The De Vere Society &#8211; Dedicated to the proposition that the works of Shakespeare were written by Edward de Vere, 17th Earl of Oxford|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref> and--> has given an address to the Shakespeare Authorship Research Centre promoting de Vere as the Shakespeare author<ref>{{cite web| last=Jacobi| first=Derek| url=http://www.authorshipstudies.org/articles/jacobi.cfm| title=Address to the Shakespeare Authorship Research Centre at Concordia University| publisher=[[Concordia University (Oregon)]]| accessdate=8 July 2015| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710044428/http://www.authorshipstudies.org/articles/jacobi.cfm| archivedate=10 July 2015| df=dmy-all}}</ref> and wrote forewords to two books on the subject in 2004 and 2005.<ref>{{cite book| editor-last=Malim| editor-first=Richard| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ua09pcd0Fo0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22great+oxford%22&source=bl&ots=wi8bOT0bO7&sig=OuMX2LlCItkmJNqIIzdzwDJPBh4&hl=en&ei=7g8cTNn9CYLfnAe2mYjrDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CBMQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=foreword&f=false| title=Foreword| work=Great Oxford: Essays on the Life and Work of Edward De Vere, 17th Earl of Oxford, 1550\u20131604| publisher=Parapress Limited| year=2004| page=3| isbn=978-1898594796}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| authorlink=Mark Anderson (writer)| last=Anderson| first=Mark| asin=B001G8WETU| title=\"Shakespeare\" by Another Name: The Life of Edward de Vere, Earl of Oxford, the Man Who Was Shakespeare| publisher=Gotham Books| date=3 August 2006| pages=xxiii\u2013xxiv| isbn=978-1592401031| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/shakespearebyano00ande}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Jacobi and fellow Shakespearean actor and director [[Mark Rylance]] initiated a \"[[Declaration of Reasonable Doubt]]\" on the authorship of Shakespeare's work, to encourage new research into the question.\n\nIn 2011, Jacobi accepted a role in the film ''[[Anonymous (2011 film)|Anonymous]]'', about the [[Oxfordian theory of Shakespeare authorship|Oxfordian theory]], starring [[Rhys Ifans]] and [[Vanessa Redgrave]]. In the film Jacobi narrates the Prologue and Epilogue, set in modern-day New York, while the film proper is set in Elizabethan England. Jacobi said that making the film was \"a very risky thing to do\", stating \"the orthodox Stratfordians are going to be apoplectic with rage\".<ref>{{harvnb|Horwitz|2010}}.</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Jacobi received the World United Creator \u2013 Platinum Demiurge Award for his tremendous contribution to uniting and promoting world literature based on his efforts to introduce William Shakespeare into modern cinema.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn March 2006, four months after civil partnerships were introduced in the United Kingdom, Jacobi registered his [[Civil partnership in the United Kingdom|civil partnership]] with theatre director Richard Clifford, his partner of 30 years.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/07/03/sir-derek-jacobi-equal-marriage-debate-a-squabble-over-nothing/| title=Sir Derek Jacobi: Equal marriage debate a \u2018squabble over nothing\u2019| work=[[Pink News]]| date=3 July 2012| accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref> They live in [[Primrose Hill]], North London.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/9359513/Derek-Jacobi-I-dont-mind-people-having-faith.-But-it-aint-for-me.html| title=Derek Jacobi: 'I don\u2019t mind people having faith. But it ain\u2019t for me'| work=The Daily Telegraph| last=Farndale| first=Nigel| date=2 July 2012| accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref> Along with his ''Vicious'' co-star Ian McKellen, he was a Grand Marshal of the 46th [[LGBT Pride March (New York City)|New York City Gay Pride March]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite news| title=Ian McKellen and Derek Jacobi in a Gay Pride March Debut| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/27/theater/ian-mckellen-and-derek-jacobi-virgins-of-the-gay-pride-march.html?hpw&rref=television&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&module=well-region&region=bottom-well&WT.nav=bottom-well| date=26 June 2015| last=Itzkoff| first=Dave| work=The New York Times| accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nJacobi is an [[atheist]].<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/9359513/Derek-Jacobi-I-dont-mind-people-having-faith.-But-it-aint-for-me.html</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 1965 || ''[[Othello (1965 British film)|Othello]]'' || [[Michael Cassio|Cassio]] ||\n|-\n| 1968 || ''[[Interlude (1968 film)|Interlude]]'' || Paul ||\n|-\n| 1970 || ''[[Three Sisters (1970 Olivier film)|Three Sisters]]'' || Andrei ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1973 || ''[[Blue Blood (1973 film)|Blue Blood]]'' || Gregory ||\n|-\n|''[[The Day of the Jackal (film)|The Day of the Jackal]]'' || Caron ||\n|-\n| 1974 || ''[[The ODESSA File (film)|The Odessa File]]'' || Klaus Wenzer ||\n|-\n| 1978 || ''[[The Medusa Touch (film)|The Medusa Touch]]'' || Townley ||\n|-\n| 1979 || ''[[The Human Factor (1979 film)|The Human Factor]]'' || Arthur Davis ||\n|-\n| 1981 || ''[[Charlotte (1981 film)|Charlotte]]'' || Daberlohn ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1982 || ''[[The Secret of NIMH]]'' || Nicodemus || Voice\n|-\n|''[[Enigma (1982 film)|Enigma]]'' || Kurt Limmer ||\n|-\n| 1985 || ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (1985 film)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' || Cyrano de Bergerac ||\n|-\n| 1988 || ''[[Little Dorrit (1987 film)|Little Dorrit]]'' || Arthur Clennam ||\n|-\n| 1989 || ''[[Henry V (1989 film)|Henry V]]'' || Chorus ||\n|-\n| 1990 || ''[[The Fool (1990 film)|The Fool]]'' || Mr. Frederick/Sir John ||\n|-\n| 1991 || ''[[Dead Again]]'' || Franklyn Madson || \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1996 || ''[[Looking for Richard]]'' || Himself ||\n|-\n|''[[Hamlet (1996 film)|Hamlet]]'' || [[King Claudius|Claudius]] ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1998 || ''[[Basil (film)|Basil]]'' || Father Frederick ||\n|-\n|''[[Love Is the Devil: Study for a Portrait of Francis Bacon|Love Is the Devil:<br/>Study for a Portrait of Francis Bacon]]'' || [[Francis Bacon (painter)|Francis Bacon]] || \n|-\n| 1999 || ''[[Molokai: The Story of Father Damien]]'' || Father Leonor Fousnel ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2000 || ''[[Up at the Villa (film)|Up at the Villa]]'' || Lucky Leadbetter ||\n|-\n|''[[Gladiator (2000 film)|G